<doc id="1189553" wikidata="Q1366002" url="?curid=1189553" title="Path (topology)">
<text>In mathematics, a path in a topological space formula_1 is a continuous function from a closed interval into formula_2 

Paths play an important role in the fields of topology and mathematical analysis. 
For example, a topological space for which there exists a path connecting any two points is said to be path-connected. Any space may be broken up into path-connected components. The set of path-connected components of a space formula_1 is often denoted formula_4 

One can also define paths and loops in pointed spaces, which are important in homotopy theory. If formula_1 is a topological space with basepoint formula_6 then a path in formula_1 is one whose initial point is formula_8. Likewise, a loop in formula_1 is one that is based at formula_8.

== Definition ==

A &quot;curve&quot; in a topological space formula_1 is a continuous function formula_12 from a non-empty and non-degenerate interval formula_13 
A &#x27; in formula_1 is a curve formula_15 whose domain formula_16 is a compact non-degenerate interval (meaning formula_17 are real numbers), where formula_18 is called the &#x27; of the path and formula_19 is called its . 
A is a path whose initial point is formula_20 and whose terminal point is formula_21 
Every non-degenerate compact interval formula_16 is homeomorphic to formula_23 which is why a is sometimes, especially in homotopy theory, defined to be a continuous function formula_24 from the closed unit interval formula_25 into formula_2
An or 0 in formula_1 is a path in formula_1 that is also a topological embedding. 

Importantly, a path is not just a subset of formula_1 that &quot;looks like&quot; a curve, it also includes a parameterization. For example, the maps formula_30 and formula_31 represent two different paths from 0 to 1 on the real line. 

A loop in a space formula_1 based at formula_33 is a path from formula_20 to formula_35 A loop may be equally well regarded as a map formula_24 with formula_37 or as a continuous map from the unit circle formula_38 to formula_1
:formula_40
This is because formula_38 is the quotient space of formula_42 when formula_43 is identified with formula_44 The set of all loops in formula_1 forms a space called the loop space of formula_2

== Homotopy of paths ==

Paths and loops are central subjects of study in the branch of algebraic topology called homotopy theory. A homotopy of paths makes precise the notion of continuously deforming a path while keeping its endpoints fixed.

Specifically, a homotopy of paths, or path-homotopy, in formula_1 is a family of paths formula_48 indexed by formula_42 such that
* formula_50 and formula_51 are fixed. 
* the map formula_52 given by formula_53 is continuous. 
The paths formula_54 and formula_55 connected by a homotopy are said to be homotopic (or more precisely path-homotopic, to distinguish between the relation defined on all continuous functions between fixed spaces). One can likewise define a homotopy of loops keeping the base point fixed.

The relation of being homotopic is an equivalence relation on paths in a topological space. The equivalence class of a path formula_56 under this relation is called the homotopy class of formula_57 often denoted formula_58 

== Path composition ==

One can compose paths in a topological space in the following manner. Suppose formula_56 is a path from formula_20 to formula_61 and formula_62 is a path from formula_61 to formula_64. The path formula_65 is defined as the path obtained by first traversing formula_56 and then traversing formula_62:
:formula_68
Clearly path composition is only defined when the terminal point of formula_56 coincides with the initial point of formula_70 If one considers all loops based at a point formula_6 then path composition is a binary operation. 

Path composition, whenever defined, is not associative due to the difference in parametrization. However it associative up to path-homotopy. That is, formula_72 Path composition defines a group structure on the set of homotopy classes of loops based at a point formula_8 in formula_2 The resultant group is called the fundamental group of formula_1 based at formula_6 usually denoted formula_77 

In situations calling for associativity of path composition &quot;on the nose,&quot; a path in formula_1 may instead be defined as a continuous map from an interval formula_79 to formula_1 for any real formula_81 (Such a path is called a Moore path.) A path formula_56 of this kind has a length formula_83 defined as formula_84 Path composition is then defined as before with the following modification:
:formula_85

Whereas with the previous definition, formula_57 formula_62, and formula_65 all have length formula_89 (the length of the domain of the map), this definition makes formula_90 What made associativity fail for the previous definition is that although formula_91 and formula_92have the same length, namely formula_93 the midpoint of formula_91 occurred between formula_62 and formula_96 whereas the midpoint of formula_92 occurred between formula_56 and formula_62. With this modified definition formula_91 and formula_92 have the same length, namely formula_102 and the same midpoint, found at formula_103 in both formula_91 and formula_92; more generally they have the same parametrization throughout.

== Fundamental groupoid ==

There is a categorical picture of paths which is sometimes useful. Any topological space formula_1 gives rise to a category where the objects are the points of formula_1 and the morphisms are the homotopy classes of paths. Since any morphism in this category is an isomorphism, this category is a groupoid called the fundamental groupoid of formula_2 Loops in this category are the endomorphisms (all of which are actually automorphisms). The automorphism group of a point formula_8 in formula_1 is just the fundamental group based at formula_8. More generally, one can define the fundamental groupoid on any subset formula_112 of formula_113 using homotopy classes of paths joining points of formula_114 This is convenient for Van Kampen&#x27;s Theorem.

